{{other people|David Farrar}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=July 2013}} {{use dmy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = David P Farrar | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = David Farrar at the New Zealand Open Source Awards.jpg | image_size = | alt = Farrar in 2010 at the New Zealand Open Source Awards | caption = Farrar in 2010 at the [[New Zealand Open Source Society|New Zealand Open Source Awards]] | birth_name = <!--only use if different from name--> | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1967|09|11|df=yes}} | birth_place = | monuments = | residence = | nationality = New Zealander | other_names = | ethnicity = <!-- Ethnicity should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Otago]], [[Victoria University of Wellington]] | occupation = Blogger, pollster, political activist | years_active = | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | home_town = | title = | term = | movement = | opponents = | boards = | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | denomination = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | spouse = | partner = <!-- unmarried life partner; use ''Name (1950–present)'' --> | children = | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | website = {{URL|kiwiblog.co.nz}} | footnotes = | box_width = }} '''David Peter Farrar''' (born 11 September 1967) is a New Zealand [[political activist]], [[wikt:Blogger|blogger]], and pollster. He is a frequent commentator in the media on Internet issues. Farrar has held many roles within the [[New Zealand National Party]] and has worked in [[New Zealand House of Representatives|Parliament]] for four National Party leaders.
His blog, ''[[Kiwiblog]]'', was the most widely read and commented on [[New Zealand blogosphere|New Zealand blog]] in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.kiwiblog.co.nz/2010/01/kiwiblogs_2009_stats.html |accessdate=28 January 2010|date=26 January 2010|publisher=Kiwiblog|title=Kiwiblog's 2009 stats|quote=2.68 million visits, 6.00 million page views, 680,000 visitors}}</ref> Farrar also maintains a presence on social networking sites Facebook and Twitter. In 2007 the ''[[National Business Review]]'' stated that: "Any realistic 'power list' produced in this country would include either Farrar or his fellow blogger and opinion leader [[Russell Brown (New Zealand)|Russell Brown]]."<ref name="nbr">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbr.co.nz/home/column_article.asp?id=19070&cid=39&cname=NBR+Comment|publisher=National Business Review|accessdate=21 September 2007|date=20 September 2007|title=Politicians will be haunted by their past on internet|author=Ben Thomas and David W Young|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611045309/http://www.nbr.co.nz/home/column_article.asp?id=19070&cid=39&cname=NBR+Comment|archivedate=11 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Education and personal life== Farrar was educated in Wellington, attending [[St Mark's Church School]] and [[Rongotai College]].{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} He is of Jewish descent on his father's side.<ref>[http://www.kiwiblog.co.nz/2012/03/nz_jewish_achievers.html Kiwiblog - NZ Jewish achievers]</ref>
He studied at the [[University of Otago]] and later at [[Victoria University of Wellington]].{{citation needed|date=June 2014}} Farrar served on the Council of Otago University as a student representative, was President of the Commerce Faculty Students' Association and chaired the Student Representative Council. While he was at the University of Otago, he was the Otago correspondent for ''Campus News'' an alternative student newspaper published by a group in Auckland but which was distributed nationwide. The newspaper was published between 1984 and 1988, and David's involvement ran from 1985 to 1987.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}
==Career== Farrar is a director of New Zealand Domain Name Registry Ltd (.nz Registry Services),<ref name=".nz Registry">{{cite web|url=http://www.nzrs.net.nz|accessdate=8 November 2006|title=New Zealand Domain Name Registry}}</ref> and manages his own [[market research]] company [http://www.curia.co.nz/ Curia]. Farrar is a member of the Market Research Society of New Zealand.
Farrar was Vice-President of the Internet Society of New Zealand, [[InternetNZ]], and is a frequent commentator in both broadcast and print media on Internet issues.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}
Previously Farrar worked as a staff member of the [[Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Leader of the Opposition]] (1999–2004), a staff member at National Party Head Office (1999 and 2004), a staff member in Ministerial Services under [[Jim Bolger]] (1996–1997) and in the [[Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet (New Zealand)|Prime Minister's Office]] under [[Jenny Shipley]] (1997–1999).{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}
Farrar writes weekly columns for the ''[[National Business Review]]'' and the iPredict futures site, and is a regular commentator on [[Radio New Zealand]] and [[Newstalk ZB]].
The ''[[New Zealand Listener]]'' 2009 [[New Zealand Listener Power List|Power List]] named Farrar the fourth most powerful person in the New Zealand media, saying "Kiwiblog has become part of the daily routine for Beltway insiders and others with an interest in politics and public policy."<ref>{{cite book|date=December 2009|title=2009 Power List|publisher=[[The New Zealand Listener]]}}</ref>
==Political involvement==
===Taxpayers' Union=== In 2013, Farrar, with Jordan Williams, established the fiscally conservative lobby group, the New Zealand Taxpayers' Union.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.taxpayers.org.nz/who_we_are | title=Who We Are | publisher=Taxpayers' Union | accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref> The Union is based on the [[TaxPayers' Alliance|United Kingdom TaxPayers Alliance]] and resulted from both Farrar and Williams' interaction with that group's founder, Matthew Elliot, through the [[International Young Democrat Union]].<ref>http://www.kiwiblog.co.nz/2013/10/the_new_zealand_taxpayers_union.html</ref>
=== Young Nationals === Farrar is an honorary life member of the [[New Zealand Young Nationals|Young Nationals]], due to his many years of service to the organisation.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}
He survived some media calls for his resignation as National Secretary when he was arrested for his part in a joke press release, along with fellow Young National Michael P Moore, announcing that maverick National MP [[Michael Laws]] had been assassinated and that the Prime Minister was one of over 10,000 suspects. The joke press-release was made with the [[New Zealand Police]] logo. Farrar and Moore were subsequently arrested, but not convicted of any crime as they chose to participate in a diversion scheme for first time offenders of minor crime. The infamous fax and related media items are now displayed at the Backbencher Bar on [[Molesworth Street in Wellington]], across the road from Parliament.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}
===Campaign manager=== At the [[New Zealand general election, 2005|2005 general election]] Farrar was the volunteer campaign manager for National's {{NZ electorate link|Wellington Central}} candidate [[Mark Blumsky]]. Blumsky was defeated in his attempt to become an electorate MP, but succeeded in entering parliament via the party list.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10426858|work=New Zealand Herald|accessdate=20 December 2007|date=4 March 2007|first=Deborah|last=Coddington|title=Making a difference, one issue at a time}}</ref>
===Political views=== Farrar professes a [[classical liberalism|classical liberal]] approach to politics, that is often compromised by his party affiliation with the [[liberal conservative]] National Party (for instance over state security powers vs individual rights <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiwiblog.co.nz/2014/05/the_campbell_live_dotcom_conspiracy_episode.html|title=The Campbell Live Dotcom conspiracy episode|work=Kiwiblog.co.nz}}</ref>) and identifies as a moderate of the center-right on the political spectrum. He was a co-chair of National's Classical Liberal Policy Advisory Group at its formation in 2004.<ref>{{cite press release |title=National Party Board approves Classical Liberal Policy Advisory Group |url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/PA0405/S00280.htm |publisher=New Zealand National Party |date=13 May 2004 |accessdate=30 June 2012}}</ref> He supported the legalisation of [[prostitution in New Zealand|prostitution]] and of [[civil union in New Zealand|civil unions in New Zealand]]. Farrar supports a [[Republicanism in New Zealand|New Zealand republic]], and is on the National Council of the [[Republican Movement of Aotearoa New Zealand|New Zealand Republican Movement]]. Economically his views are more in keeping with those of parties to the right of the National Party, such as the [[market fundamentalism]] of the minority<ref>2014 NZ Election, Party results. http://www.electionresults.govt.nz/electionresults_2014/partystatus.html</ref> [[ACT New Zealand|ACT]] party.
Farrar has appeared before Parliamentary select committees on a range of issues, including the [[Electoral Finance Act 2007|Electoral Finance Bill]]. He often publishes his submissions on his blog.<ref name="efb_sub">{{cite web |url=http://www.kiwiblog.co.nz/2007/09/my_submission_on_the_electoral_finance_bill.html |title=My submission on the Electoral Finance Bill|date=10 September 2007|publisher=Kiwiblog|author=David Farrar|authorlink=David Farrar (blogger)|accessdate=23 September 2007}}</ref>
