{{other people|Timothy Green}} {{Infobox NFL player |name =Tim Green |number = 99 |position =[[Linebacker]] / [[Defensive end]] |birth_date ={{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1963|12|16}} |birth_place =[[Liverpool, New York]] |death_date = |death_place = |height_ft = 6 |height_in = 2 |weight_lbs = 249 |high_school = [[Liverpool High School|Liverpool (NY)]] |college =[[Syracuse Orange football|Syracuse]] |draftyear = 1986 |draftround = 1 |draftpick = 17 |pastteams = * [[Atlanta Falcons]] ({{NFL Year|1986}}–{{NFL Year|1993}}) |highlights = |statweek= |statseason= |statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Tackles]] |statvalue1=-- |statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack]]s |statvalue2=24.0 |statlabel3=[[Pass deflected|Pass deflections]] |statvalue3=-- |statlabel4=[[Interception]]s |statvalue4=-- |statlabel5=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]] |statvalue5=-- |statlabel6=[[Safety (gridiron football score)|Safeties]] |statvalue6=1 |nfl = 2500903 |pfr = GreeTi20 }} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Tim Green | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1963|12|16|mf=y}} | birth_place =[[Liverpool, New York]] | occupation = Sports commentator, attorney, author, former linebacker |years_active =1991&ndash;present | genre = | movement = | notableworks = | influences = | influenced = | website = {{URL|http://www.timgreenbooks.com/}} }}
'''Timothy John Green ''' (born December 16, 1963) is a former American [[American football|football]] player, a radio and television personality, and a best-selling author. He was a [[linebacker]] and [[defensive end]] with the [[Atlanta Falcons]] of the [[National Football League]], a commentator for [[National Public Radio]], and the former host of the 2005 revival of ''[[A Current Affair (U.S. TV series)|A Current Affair]]'' on Fox.
==Biography== Green graduated from [[Liverpool High School]] in 1982 and attended nearby [[Syracuse University]]. He graduated ''[[Latin honors|summa cum laude]]'' in 1986, and from SU's [[Syracuse University College of Law|College of Law]] in 1994. He was named a two-time Academic All-American.<ref>http://cuse.com/sports/2001/8/7/verizon.aspx</ref> Green was a first round selection in the [[1986 NFL Draft]], taken 17th overall by the [[1986 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GreeTi20.htm.</ref> Following his eight-year playing career, he was a commentator for the [[NFL on Fox]] and a co-host of ''Find My Family'' with [[Lisa Joyner]] on ABC Television in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abc.go.com/shows/find-my-family/bio/tim-green/338352 |title=ABC.com - Television Shows & Programming |publisher=Abc.go.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128041111/http://abc.go.com/shows/find-my-family/bio/tim-green/338352 |archivedate=2010-01-28 |df= }}</ref>
In December 2011, Green was named a winner of the [[Silver Anniversary Awards (NCAA)|NCAA Silver Anniversary Award]], given annually to six former NCAA student-athletes for distinguished career accomplishment on the 25th anniversary of their college graduation.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.ncaa.org/wps/portal/ncaahome?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=/ncaa/NCAA/Media+and+Events/Press+Room/News+Release+Archive/2010/Awards+and+Scholarships/20101201+Silver+Award+Rls |title=NCAA Names Silver Anniversary Winners |publisher=NCAA |date=December 1, 2010 |accessdate=April 4, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205115128/http://www.ncaa.org/wps/portal/ncaahome?WCM_GLOBAL_CONTEXT=%2Fncaa%2FNCAA%2FMedia+and+Events%2FPress+Room%2FNews+Release+Archive%2F2010%2FAwards+and+Scholarships%2F20101201+Silver+Award+Rls |archivedate=December 5, 2010 |df= }}</ref>
Green's book ''Football Genius'' made ''[[The New York Times]]'' best-seller list of children's chapter books.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/27/nyregion/27green.html?ref=nyregion]</ref> He serves on the National Writer's Project Writing Council<ref>http://www.nwp.org/cs/public/print/doc/about/writers_council.csp</ref> and has written over thirty novels in the adult suspense and youth sports genres.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Tim-Green/e/B000AQ3XK8/ref=la_B000AQ3XK8_pg_2?rh=n%3A283155%2Cp_82%3AB000AQ3XK8&page=2&ie=UTF8&qid=1434033926</ref>
As an attorney, Green has been counsel with the law firm Barclay Damon LLP in New York State since February 1999. He has assisted in growing and developing the firm's client base focusing in energy and intellectual property.<ref>http://barclaydamon.com/profiles/Timothy-J-Green</ref> In May 2014, Green partnered with former Assistant District Attorney Scott Brenneck. Their firm, Team Green Lawyers, PLLC, is composed of former prosecutors that are now working privately and offering criminal defense services.<ref>http://www.teamgreenlawyers.com/#!attorneys/galleryPage</ref>
Green lives in Upstate New York with his wife, Illyssa, five children, and three dogs.<ref>http://timgreenbooks.com/meet-tim/about/</ref>
On November 14, 2018, Green announced in a Facebook post that he has a slow-progressing form of [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]].<ref>https://www.syracuse.com/orangefootball/index.ssf/2018/11/former_syracuse_football_legend_tim_green_says_he_has_als.html</ref> On November 18, he was featured on ''[[60 Minutes]]'', discussing his life and struggles with the disease.
